 
<!-- PJG STAG 4700 -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=11 g=1 f=1 -->
Including 1994 model year engines in the emissions trading and 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
banking program and raises an issue whether engines manufactured in 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
model year 1994 prior to the promulgation of this rule may be 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
included in the program. A similar situation was confronted in the 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
original banking and trading rule. There, EPA allowed banking for 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
the full 1990 model year, even though the rule was promulgated on 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
July 26, 1990. 
<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=11 g=1 f=3 -->
See
<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=11 g=1 f=1 -->
 55 FR 30584, 30587. In that case, EPA placed 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
certain restrictions on the inclusion of 1990 model year engines, 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
to ensure credits were only given for significant reductions below 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
the 1990 standards. This was to ensure that ``windfall'' credits 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
from exceeding the arguably ``lax'' pre-1991 standards would not be 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
used in the transition to the more stringent 1991 standards. As a 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
result, if no restrictions on trading and banking were imposed, 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
then the engines that had always exceeded the 1990 standards would 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
for the first time be able to use the extra reductions as 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
``windfall'' credits to offset engines that did not yet meet the new 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
and more stringent 1991 standards. 
<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=11 g=1 f=3 -->
See
<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=11 g=1 f=1 -->
 55 FR at 30597. 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
EPA does not believe such restrictions are necessary in this 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
case. Since 1991, engines using other fuels, such as methanol, 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
have been able to generate credits to offset higher emitting 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
engines. EPA believes that gaseous-fueled engines should have an 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
equal opportunity to use such credits as gasoline-, diesel-, and 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
methanol-fueled engines, now that emissions standards and test 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
procedures are in place in time for the 1994 model year. As EPA 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
explained in the response to comments in the trading and banking 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
final rule, CNG engines were not included at that time due to the 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
absence of standards, test procedures, and certification protocols. 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=11 g=1 f=3 -->
See id
<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=11 g=1 f=1 -->
 at 30609. Now that these rules are in place, there is no 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
longer any reason to disadvantage CNG engines vis a vis other 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
fuels. 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
In addition, EPA does not believe that the credits 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
manufacturers might obtain from gaseous-fueled engines are 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
``windfall,'' since they arguably would not have manufactured such 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
engines in model year 1994 but for EPA's actions to provide an 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
incentive to do so. Rather, EPA believes manufacturers had an 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
incentive to manufacture gaseous-fueled engines based on EPA 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
actions prior to this final rule. EPA proposed these standards in 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
November 1992, and began developing these standards substantially 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
before that. EPA believes this overall incentive further supports 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
allowing manufacturers to include all 1994 model year engines in 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
the trading and banking program. 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
The aftermarket conversion certification procedures contained 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
in today's rule are available to converters as a way of obtaining 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
an exemption from the tampering prohibition. Since this procedure 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
creates an exemption and is optional it will be available upon 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
publication in the 
<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=11 g=1 f=4 -->
Federal Register
<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=11 g=1 f=1 -->
. EPA's current policy toward 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
conversions will continue to apply to aftermarket conversions which 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
have not received an exemption under this new program.
