<!-- PJG ITAG l=83 g=1 f=1 -->
B. New Vehicle Standards 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=11 g=1 f=1 -->
The new gaseous-fueled vehicle and engine emission standards 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
contained in today's notice are effective with the 1997 model year. 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
Optional compliance prior to the 1997 model year is available to 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
manufacturers who wish to include their vehicles and engines in 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
emissions averaging, trading and banking programs, as well as the 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
CAFE program in the case of natural gas-fueled vehicles. 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
In general, the Agency seeks to control vehicles operated on 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
alternative fuels so that their emissions are no greater than their 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
petroleum-fueled counterparts. Thus, the exhaust emission 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
standards for gaseous-fueled vehicles are numerically equivalent to 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
those which apply to other, currently regulated vehicles and 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
engines. The only significant departure from this approach is in 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
the area of hydrocarbon (HC) standards for natural gas fueled 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
vehicles and engines. Prior to the 1994 model year, regulated 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
vehicles (
<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=11 g=1 f=3 -->
i.e.
<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=11 g=1 f=1 -->
, gasoline, petroleum diesel and methanol) are only 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
required to meet total hydrocarbon (THC) standards. However, 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
beginning with the 1994 model year, currently regulated light-duty 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
vehicles and light-duty trucks will also be required to meet 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
separate nonmethane hydrocarbon (NMHC) standards as part of the 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
Tier 1 requirements of the Clean Air Act.
<FOOTCITE>4</FOOTCITE>
 For natural gas-fueled 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
light-duty vehicles and light-duty trucks only the NMHC standards 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
will apply. In the case of natural gas-fueled heavy-duty engines, 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
NMHC standards which provide the same degree of NMHC control as the 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
current THC standards provide for petroleum-fueled vehicles will 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
apply. In the case of LPG vehicles and engines, the HC standards 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
are the same as those for currently regulated vehicles. A summary 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
of today's gaseous-fueled vehicle emission standards is contained 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
in Tables 1 through 4.
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

